content.text: The ElizaOS community is actively discussing development, plugins, and technical issues. Odilitime, the lead dev on Spartan (a DeFi utility project), is helping new developers get started by recommending they read the code and explore plugins at github.com/elizaos-plugins/. A blockchain + AI engineer named aicodeflow joined the community, expressing interest in contributing to agent autonomy with constraints, particularly in areas like onchain execution layers with guardrails, prediction markets, and observability tools.

Several developers are experiencing technical issues. One user is having trouble with the Discord plugin not detecting server ID, username, or server owner despite having proper permissions and intents. Another developer encountered a database migration error when running 'elizaos start' a second time, with the community suggesting using 'ELIZA_ALLOW_DESTRUCTIVE_MIGRATIONS=true' or the 'elizaos dev' command as solutions.

The core developers are discussing various projects and improvements. Stan mentioned finding ways to improve latency on the monorepo and plans to push multiple PRs. Odilitime shared that Neo rolled out a Rust-inspired ElizaOS called Zoey (zoey.xyz), which received fire emoji reactions. The team also noted that ElizaOS was featured in a tweet about AI bubbles.

There's also discussion about integration opportunities, with one user sharing a library for experimenting with x402 protocol integration with ElizaOS (npm i @alleyboss/micropay-solana-x402-paywall). Community members are sharing resources like RSS feeds that could be refined into a dashboard with other data sources.

The community appears to be active with regular greetings and casual conversations. Some members are discussing DegenAI and its relationship with ElizaOS, with one user suggesting ElizaOS might go 'parabolic' again based on GitHub activity. There's also mention of 'earning agents' that make money for users.

categories.title: Recent GitHub Issues in elizaOS/eliza Repository

content.text:
Two recent issues have been reported in the elizaOS/eliza GitHub repository:

1. Issue #6332 reports a performance problem where Turbo build is consuming excessive memory, reaching over 21GB. This could potentially impact build times and system performance for developers working with the eliza project.

2. Issue #6331 documents a bug where users encounter a "Model not found" error when attempting to use agent IDs with API endpoints. This issue likely affects API functionality and integration capabilities.
Between January 6-7, 2026, the elizaos/eliza repository had no new pull requests (0 merged), 2 new issues were opened, and there were 2 active contributors working on the project during this period.
